==English==

===Etymology===
Middle English ''[[malliable]]'', borrowed from late Latin ''[[malleabilis|malleābilis]]'', derived from ''[[malleare|malleāre]]'' "to hammer", from ''[[malleus]]'' "hammer", from Proto-Indo-European ''*mal-ni-'' "crushing", an extended variant of ''*melH₂-'' "crush, grind".

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈmæliəbəl/}}, {{SAMPA|/"m{li@b@l/}}
* {{audio|en-us-malleable.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{hyphenation|mal|le|a|ble}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Able to be [[hammer]]ed into [[thin]] [[sheet]]s; capable of being [[extend]]ed or [[shape]]d by [[beat]]ing with a [[hammer]], or by the pressure of [[roller]]s.
# (''metaphorical'') [[flexible|Flexible]], [[liable]] to [[change]].
#: ''My opinion on the subject is '''malleable'''.''

